SIMPLE: transform
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Transform
<hw>Trans*form"</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. &
p. p.</pos> <conjf>Transformed</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb.
n.</pos> <conjf>Transforming</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[L.
<ets>transformare</ets>, <ets>transformatum</ets>; <ets>trans</ets>
across, over + <ets>formare</ets> to from: cf. F.
<ets>transformer</ets>. See <er>Form</er>, <pos>v. t.</pos>]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>To change the form of; to change in shape or
appearance; to metamorphose; <as>as, a caterpillar is ultimately
<ex>transformed</ex> into a butterfly</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Love may <qex>transform</qex> me to an oyster.</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To change into another substance; to transmute;
<as>as, the alchemists sought to <ex>transform</ex> lead into
gold</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To change in nature, disposition, heart, character,
or the like; to convert.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Be ye <qex>transformed</qex> by the renewing of your mind.</q>
<rj><qau>Rom. xii. 2.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Math.)</fld> <def>To change, as an algebraic
expression or geometrical figure, into another from without altering its
value.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transform</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Transform
<hw>Trans*form"</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <def>To be changed in form; to be
metamorphosed.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>His hair <qex>transforms</qex> to down.</q>
<rj><qau>Addison.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Transformable</ent>⟦br⟧
